pr_title: initial replacements of module system
pr_body:
This Pr is under the purview of   GSOC'20 project 
* all native `require and module.exports of nodejs` has been changed to `es6 export and import` in src folder !
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 433046448, 'comment_body': "I noticed some errors here. I think we need something like this to load the Tone Context module and to be able to set the context. For some reason we're not able to dispose of the context. We'll get an eslint error that Context is not used and we'll need to ignore that error or figure out how to use it :)

```
import Tone from 'Tone/core/Tone';
import Context from 'Tone/core/Context';

const audiocontext = new window.AudioContext();

// Tone and p5.sound share the same audio context
Tone.setContext(audiocontext);", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 5, 23, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 433047345, 'comment_body': "for a future PR, this may be an opportunity to decouple p5.sound from p5. In the app module, we could check to see if p5 exists on the page. If it doesn't, we could behave differently, allowing p5.sound to be a stand-alone module. Just a thought...", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 1, 5, 27, 57, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 442901171, 'comment_body': "yes that was really helpfull , the problem was due to Tone.Context was not in the scope of the current module ,
also 
doing 
import 'Tone/core/Context' solved the problem of linter!
@therewasaguy ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 19, 15, 20, 9, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443260439, 'comment_body': 'why this version?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 21, 56, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443260726, 'comment_body': "can we get rid of `'use strict'` now that we're on es6, where [Module code is always strict mode code](http://www.ecma-international.org/ecma-262/6.0/#sec-strict-mode-code)?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 1, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443261229, 'comment_body': 'looks like this has changed to `TONE_SILENCE_LOGGING` https://github.com/Tonejs/Tone.js/blob/f17249691d36ca38a9b9c1a803bbde4dd4be070f/Tone/core/Global.ts#L65', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 8, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443261700, 'comment_body': "the envelope isn't working after this change. I wonder if the API for TransportTimelineSignal has changed?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 15, 14, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443262754, 'comment_body': "it looks like this private method of TimelineSignal does not exist on TransportTimelineSignal. I don't see any reason that we can't just use `getValueAtTime`, though?

We aren't able to get `value` from the timeline signal, instead it returns the number directly: https://tonejs.github.io/docs/13.8.25/TransportTimelineSignal.html#getvalueattime", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 30, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443262895, 'comment_body': "same as the comment above - `TransportTimelineSignal._searchAfter` does not exist anymore (best not to use private methods of a dependency!)

I don't see any reason why we couldn't change to something like this
```
const previousValue = +this._voicesInUse.getValueAtTime(time);
this._voicesInUse.setValueAtTime(time, previousValue + value);
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 32, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443264089, 'comment_body': 'it seems we cannot set a value to be negative with the new TransportTimelineSignal API. I think this can just be `0`?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 21, 22, 49, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443528937, 'comment_body': 'This was just an experiment oriented thing, like i was testing what things breaks if we upgarde üòµ,
Anyways i dont see any diff after that, so i think we should switch back to 10th one', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 12, 40, 45, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443531661, 'comment_body': 'I have a different view over this, actually our modules are transpiled into es5 or lower by babel,
So in browser our code would still be non es6 and hence browser need this
*use strict*
Declaration 
For operating in strict mode. ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 12, 45, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443533436, 'comment_body': 'Actually i have to make a fix there, the actuall api is something different!
No worries, i will be doing that 
üëç', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 12, 48, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443534311, 'comment_body': 'May be because this docs are for 13.8.25 version and we are using its
0.x version ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 12, 50, 24, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443876365, 'comment_body': 'we are using the older version and hence there is no need to worry about that ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 23, 20, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443876718, 'comment_body': '@therewasaguy  we reverted back to the older tone " 0.10.0"  now its fines i guess ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 23, 21, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443876900, 'comment_body': 'not a problem we reverted back to  the older tone !', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 23, 22, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443877099, 'comment_body': 'same ! here too', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 22, 23, 22, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443951973, 'comment_body': "we'll want to update at some point, but happy to do that in a separate PR", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 4, 18, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443952078, 'comment_body': "yes, we'll want to update at some point, but we can do that in a separate PR if it's not required for this one", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 4, 18, 34, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443959151, 'comment_body': "hmm, that's a good point! Still, we don't need strict mode in our modules (any files in the `src` directory) because they're already in strict mode even after compilation with es6.

We can verify that by removing strict mode, and then doing any of the things that aren't allowed in es5's strict mode from this article https://flaviocopes.com/javascript-strict-mode/  and verifying that it still throws an error for the developer. My understanding of strict mode is that its audience is primarily developers because it throws errors that would otherwise be silent in ES5. So people who are working on p5.sound library will still get the same errors now that we're using ES6 modules. Meanwhile, people using the compiled library won't be modifying the library, so they don't need the library to be in strict mode.

We do still want to have `'use strict';` in in test files, since we haven't turned those into es6 modules yet.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 4, 49, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443960244, 'comment_body': "The compiled versions of the library are still missing a lot of code, any idea why that is?

In general I'd recommend excluding `lib` files from PR's until we're ready to bump the library version number. But, if you want to include, make sure they compiled successfully !", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 4, 53, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443967629, 'comment_body': "okay ! that's the nice  point to consider and i will be removing the 'strict mode' ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 5, 20, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443972390, 'comment_body': '@therewasaguy  
i am not focusing on lib/ in my latest commits , and if you are checking it after my latest commit , build the file once again , i dont think the file is shrunk , it is 443kb as seen on my  linux  machine!', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 5, 35, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 443973446, 'comment_body': '@therewasaguy  i have added only this extra line  apart from import/export thing , actully i missed makinng Context in our module scope earlier and that was the actual problem ! ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 23, 5, 39, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445146667, 'comment_body': "successfully removed the 'strict mode' declaration!", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 24, 20, 17, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445310024, 'comment_body': 'great question @endurance21 ! Without the default keyword, we'd be using a named export, and I guess "p5.Effect" is not a valid name.

We could do something like
`export const Effect = p5.Effect;` because then we'd be giving the export a valid name, which we could import as `import { Effect } from 'effect'`

and let's remove this comment from the code :)', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 5, 9, 55, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445312533, 'comment_body': "just an observation: there are a few examples like this where we're dependent on the order of imports. If app.js imported oscillator before panner, `p5.Panner` would not exist.

A better approach would be to `import p5Panner from 'panner'` here in the oscillator module.

This doesn't need to be done as part of this PR, but I noticed we're not exporting anything from p5.Panner right now...should we be consistent and have at least a default export for every module?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 5, 19, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445454150, 'comment_body': 'we can also do smth like this 
`
const Effect  = p5.Effect
`

`
export default Effect 
`

and we dont have to chnage anything in other files importing them ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 10, 14, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445455898, 'comment_body': 'we ll see if we need to export smth out of  them in future !', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 10, 17, 46, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 445580876, 'comment_body': 'why this change?

Not opposed to it but I do think we should be consistent about using names exports (like this one) or default exports?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 6, 25, 14, 0, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 454786743, 'comment_body': 'rather than use .prototype, we can place these methods within the class, similar to the `constructor` method (which should be at the top), like

```
class FFT {
...
  setInput(source) {
   ...
  }
}
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 4, 39, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455575726, 'comment_body': '
and yes for sure , we can do so , but a Big BUT is that , 
declaring the method this way , significantly helps in memory optimizations ! 
as we can see here 
https://www.thecodeship.com/web-development/methods-within-constructor-vs-prototype-in-javascript/

should we consider those memory optimization techniques ! ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 7, 45, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455877182, 'comment_body': "Great point to bring up and I'm looking forward to hearing more! Do the con's of memory outweigh the pros of having access to vars inside the constructor? 

https://stackoverflow.com/questions/4508313/advantages-of-using-prototype-vs-defining-methods-straight-in-the-constructor", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 15, 32, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'LilaShiba', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 455891111, 'comment_body': "These links are from before ES6.

It's true that we don't want to define the method _within_ the constructor.

To clarify: I'm suggesting that we define it _next to / after_ the constructor, as part of the class. This is syntactic sugar for adding the method to the prototype.

```
class FFT {
  constructor() { ... }
  setInput(source) { ... }
}
```", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 16, 15, 52, 6, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456153635, 'comment_body': '@therewasaguy  wow! i just confirmed it , i made a class and tested it .prototype and its object  __proto__ and wolla !
i saw , method was  present in there in its prototype object ! 
That was a nice concept !  i ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 17, 0, 36, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456168837, 'comment_body': 'That syntactical sugar will get you every time.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 17, 1, 32, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'LilaShiba', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 456468309, 'comment_body': '@kyle1james  ohk ohk ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 17, 14, 12, 44, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 457077346, 'comment_body': 'We can use es6 get / set instead of Object.defineProperties/Property

https://javascript.info/property-accessors

That can be a separate pr, if not this one.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 20, 5, 55, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 457115641, 'comment_body': 'Okay i will keep that in separate pr ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 20, 7, 6, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_review_comments:

pr_title: modernized the  TESTING architecture of the codebase { GSOC}
pr_body:
## MORE CLEANER AND INTUITIVE TESTING ARCHITECTURE 

* getting rid of requirejs .finally ! 
* used es6 imports 
* used npm to download "chai" and "mocha" and removed the cached version in test/testDeps/chai.js , test/testDeps/mocha.js
thus reducing the `size` of the codebase ! 

* can be further linked to karma.js for headless testing ! { future goals} 
* can be further used for integrating in CI environment !

pr_title: added check for  [bins] argument in fft method of P5,  along with unit Test( in es6 style)
pr_body:
issue :
![safebins](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43696525/77712922-22d3c600-6ffb-11ea-986f-c4eb37671c47.png)


the bins arguments is very vulnerable , as there is no check to what user provides as  the input to bins argument  , suppose the user enters a negative value of bins by mistake , then it's a crash !
so there must be a check to what user gives input as  "bins" arguments"


solution : 
* added a filter (safeBins) to what user enters as argument .
![this bins](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43696525/77713158-a8f00c80-6ffb-11ea-86ee-7da872e15777.png)

* checks are esablished as shown 
![safeBins](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43696525/77713279-fbc9c400-6ffb-11ea-912c-01b9d7e7f413.png)
* added a unit test for the function
![testSafeBins](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/43696525/77713348-2c116280-6ffc-11ea-90dc-84d3317e8b20.png)
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 400621236, 'comment_body': 'should this be a `console.warn` or `console.error` ?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 3, 27, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 400621649, 'comment_body': "do we need to add this to the p5 prototype, or can this be a private method that is only used internally?

If it's only added to the prototype for the purpose of writing a test, I think the test should instead be on the public methods that utilize this function behind the scenes.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 3, 28, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 400632629, 'comment_body': 'all of these tests "handle" _invalid_ values by setting a default value.

Other libraries might choose to throw an error when a user enters an invalid value. Since we're not throwing an error, I wonder if there's a way we could verify that an error message was logged to the console?


It is useful to test behavior when a user provides invalid values. But we probably also want to test for valid value(s). For example, with the tests so far, the method could be changed to _always_ return 1024 and we wouldn't realize this bug.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 4, 13, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 400633146, 'comment_body': "this üö´ means that the file doesn't end with a new line. I don't think it's a big deal but some do, so I think it's a best practice to end files with a new line :) https://thoughtbot.com/blog/no-newline-at-end-of-file", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 4, 15, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 400650423, 'comment_body': 'ya ! this is the bug , if anyone changes the function to always return 1024 then also this test will pass . okay i will be including that ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 5, 23, 17, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 401198252, 'comment_body': 'a warning would be forgiving and error will remind user of its mistake ,
but here as even after the user enters wrong value we assign it a default one so it think , we are not breaking the operation so i think giving warning will be legitimate console.warn ()



', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 20, 35, 3, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 401200742, 'comment_body': '@therewasaguy  the main problem i face was using AMD here , I was unable to use safeBins defined in src/helper.js in test/tests/helpers.test.js , so I decided to put this method in prototype object of p5 ,
and I am realising now , that it is not the good way of doing it !,
so  I will add tests on   public function that will wrap this function ! and remove it from p5.prototype', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 3, 31, 20, 39, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'endurance21', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 401202460, 'comment_body': 'are you talking about "\n" or what ?
 
i don't see this newline  in any of the test file in our library! should I use it everywhere ?

pr_body:

## some highlights 

* installing latest p5 from npm version "1.0.0"  

* ### post-install Scripts  :
   * copying  p5.js file from /node_modules to /lib folder .
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 451946948, 'comment_body': "in future PR's, no need to include the lib files if src files haven't changed", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 3, 45, 31, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451947756, 'comment_body': "I think we'll want both the `.min` and the unminified version of p5.js.

And I'm wondering if we should just copy the file like `cp ./node_modules/p5/lib/p5* ./lib`, rather than move and delete it? No harm in leaving node_modules intact, right?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 3, 49, 19, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451947915, 'comment_body': 'did you mean to change this eslint configuration as part of this PR?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 3, 50, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 451956860, 'comment_body': 'it seems like this is the same as "latest", which might be a bit easier to read?

Also, funny that it installs a file that says "0.10.2" at the top with this, and with "latest" too. That seems to be the latest version in npm and we should publish p5.js with "1.0.0" !', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 9, 4, 29, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 452056644, 'comment_body': 'I was just ensuring less size of repo , however it would be more meaningful if a developer would know oh yes, this p5.js has come from npm!!!.

In the future, I recommend only adding specific files to the commit, to avoid adding files that aren't related to the PR. `git add -p` (https://gist.github.com/mattlewissf/9958704) is really useful for this, it lets us choose which modifications we want to add to staging. That way, we can commit these sorts of auto-style fixes separately.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 15, 4, 34, 13, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'therewasaguy', 'type': 'User'}]
